{
	"nodes":[
		{"id":"3bb45b8281237e3f","x":-379,"y":-129,"width":739,"height":689,"type":"text","text":"New question: You're in a microservices setup with Kubernetes. A service crashes while processing a RabbitMQ message. How do you make sure that message isn't lost and doesn't get processed twice? Walk me through your exact setup.\n\n\n### What you need to improve (this is what they probably want to hear):\n\n1. **Manual Acknowledgment** – You need to say you’re using **manual ack**, not auto-ack. With noAck: false.\n2. **Kubernetes + RabbitMQ** – The key pattern they’re looking for is **at-least-once delivery + idempotency**.\n    - Message stays unacked if pod dies → RabbitMQ redelivers it.\n    - You **must** make your consumer **idempotent** (use unique message ID or event ID, check in DB before processing).\n3. **Don’t rely on Kubernetes for deduplication** – Kubernetes doesn’t solve double processing. That’s your job in code.\n\n**Quick version of the strong answer:**\n\n> \"I’d use **manual acknowledgment** — only ack after the entire processing finishes and I’ve persisted the result. If the pod crashes, the message stays unacked and RabbitMQ will redeliver it. To prevent double processing, every message carries a unique eventId or correlationId. Before doing any work, I first check in PostgreSQL (or Redis) if that ID was already processed. If yes — I ack and skip. If not — process, save, then ack. That gives me exactly-once semantics even with at-least-once delivery from the queue.\""},
		{"id":"4a611c03e6c8acc9","x":420,"y":-129,"width":653,"height":260,"type":"text","text":"Dead letter queue config\n> \"I’d configure the main queue with a **dead letter exchange** and **dead letter routing key**. After 3 failed retries, I’d reject the message with requeue: false so it goes to the DLQ. On the DLQ side, I’d have a separate consumer or a monitoring alert that picks up these failed messages so we can investigate why they keep failing — maybe bad data, schema change, or a bug in the consumer.\""}
	],
	"edges":[]
}